<paragraph blockId="119.[151,1437,1833,2038]" lastBlockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" lastPageId="120" lastPageNumber="121" pageId="119" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,460,1833,1858]" pageId="119" pageNumber="120">Synoptic description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[476,562,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="119" pageNumber="120">Worker.</emphasis>
Medium-sized (TL 
<quantity box="[816,935,1833,1858]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="119" pageNumber="120" unit="mm" value="10.5" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="9.0">9–12 mm</quantity>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bingham, C. T." box="[956,1139,1833,1858]" pageId="119" pageNumber="120" refId="ref132962" refString="Bingham, C. T. (1903) The fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Hymenoptera, Vol. II. Ants and Cuckoo-wasps. Taylor and Francis, London, 506 pp." type="book" year="1903">Bingham, 1903</bibRefCitation>
) ants with the standard characters of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Forel" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[306,404,1869,1894]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="119" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ponerini">Ponerini</taxonomicName>
. Mandibles short, triangular and massive, with a basal groove. Clypeus with a denticulate anterior margin. Eyes fairly small, placed anterior of head midline, with a subtle preocular carina (often difficult to distinguish from the striate sculpturing of the head). Pronotum with a short spine at each anterodorsal corner. Metanotal groove very shallowly impressed or reduced to a simple suture. Propodeum narrowed dorsally, the posterior margins with shallow denticulate ridges. Propodeal spiracle ovoid. Metatibial spur formula (1s, 1p). Petiole squamiform, with a sharp denticulate and emarginate dorsal margin. Gaster with only a weak girdling constriction between pre- and postsclerites of A4. Stridulitrum present on pretergite of A4. Head and mesosoma deeply striate, the gaster only lightly punctate. Head and body with scattered pilosity and only light pubescence. Color ferrugineous to black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" box="[199,1116,295,320]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis box="[199,279,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Queen.</emphasis>
Similar to worker but larger (TL 
<quantity box="[655,779,295,320]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" unit="mm" value="12.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="11.0">11–13 mm</quantity>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bingham, C. T." box="[790,964,295,320]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" refId="ref132962" refString="Bingham, C. T. (1903) The fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Hymenoptera, Vol. II. Ants and Cuckoo-wasps. Taylor and Francis, London, 506 pp." type="book" year="1903">Bingham, 1903</bibRefCitation>
) and winged.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" box="[199,634,332,357]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis box="[199,264,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Male.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion box="[270,310,332,357]" country="South Sudan" name="Lakes" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">See</collectingRegion>
description in 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, F." box="[478,630,332,357]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" refId="ref162573" refString="Smith, F. (1858) Catalogue of hymenopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum. Part VI. Formicidae. British Museum, London, 216 pp." type="book" year="1858">Smith (1858)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" box="[199,750,367,392]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis box="[199,273,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Larva.</emphasis>
Described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Wheeler, G. C. &amp; Wheeler, J." box="[435,745,367,392]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="604 - 672" refId="ref166964" refString="Wheeler, G. C. &amp; Wheeler, J. (1952) The ant larvae of the subfamily Ponerinae - Part II. American Midland Naturalist, 48, 604 - 672. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2307 / 2422200" type="journal article" year="1952">Wheeler &amp; Wheeler (1952)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,496,404,429]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Geographic distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[504,668,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[504,668,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to Southeast Asia, where its range stretches from 
<collectingCountry box="[1378,1436,404,429]" name="India" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">India</collectingCountry>
to the 
<collectingCountry box="[221,347,439,464]" name="Philippines" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[566,633,439,464]" name="China" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">China</collectingCountry>
to the 
<collectingRegion box="[710,946,439,464]" country="Indonesia" name="Nusa Tenggara Timur" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Lesser Sunda Islands</collectingRegion>
of southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1087,1196,439,464]" name="Indonesia" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Creighton, W. S." box="[1211,1398,439,464]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="150 - 154" refId="ref135959" refString="Creighton, W. S. (1929) New forms of Odontoponera transversa. Psyche (Camb.), 36, 150 - 154. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1155 / 1929 / 92879" type="journal article" year="1929">Creighton, 1929</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="120" pageNumber="121" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,465,476,501]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Ecology and behavior.</emphasis>
Virtually nothing is known about the social behavior of 
<taxonomicName box="[1107,1270,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1107,1270,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the genus has received some attention from ecologists due to its abundance. For example, 
<bibRefCitation author="Wheeler, W. M. &amp; Chapman, J. W." box="[1047,1367,511,536]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="47 - 73" refId="ref168181" refString="Wheeler, W. M. &amp; Chapman, J. W. (1925) The ants of the Philippine Islands. Part I, Dorylinae and Ponerinae. Philippine Journal of Science, 28, 47 - 73." type="journal article" year="1925">Wheeler &amp; Chapman (1925)</bibRefCitation>
noted the abundance of 
<taxonomicName box="[347,510,548,573]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[347,510,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at a site in the 
<collectingCountry box="[676,805,548,573]" name="Philippines" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Philippines</collectingCountry>
, and it was common in a Bornean rainforest (
<bibRefCitation author="Berghoff, S. M. &amp; Maschwitz, U. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E." pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="149 - 157" refId="ref132637" refString="Berghoff, S. M., Maschwitz, U. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E. (2003) Influence of the hypogaeic army ant Dorylus (Dichthadia) laevigatus on tropical arthropod communities. Oecologia, 135, 149 - 157." type="journal article" year="2003">
Berghoff 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
, 2003
</bibRefCitation>
), was one of the dominant ants in a study in 
<collectingCountry box="[778,873,583,608]" name="Vietnam" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Eguchi, K. &amp; Bui, T. V. &amp; Yamane, S." box="[890,1115,583,608]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="445 - 457" refId="ref140371" refString="Eguchi, K., Bui, T. V. &amp; Yamane, S. (2004) A preliminary study on foraging distance and nesting sites of ants in indo-Chinese lowland vegetation (Insects, Hymenoptera, Formicidae). Sociobiology, 43 (3), 445 - 457." type="journal article" year="2004">
Eguchi 
<emphasis box="[980,1039,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
), was the dominant groundnesting ant in a study in 
<collectingCountry box="[421,521,620,645]" name="Thailand" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Thailand</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Sitthicharoenchai, D. &amp; Chantarasawat, N." box="[535,1006,620,645]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="67 - 74" refId="ref162246" refString="Sitthicharoenchai, D. &amp; Chantarasawat, N. (2006) Ant species diversity in the establishing area for Advanced Technology Institute at Lai-Nan Sub-district, Wiang Sa District, Nan Province, Thailand. Natural History Journal of Chulalongkorn University, 6 (2), 67 - 74." type="journal article" year="2006">Sitthicharoenchai &amp; Chantarasawat, 2006</bibRefCitation>
), was one of the most abundant ants in a forest in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[391,458,655,680]" name="China" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">China</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Zhou, H. &amp; Chen, J. &amp; Chen, F." box="[477,688,655,680]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="317 - 324" refId="ref169966" refString="Zhou, H., Chen, J. &amp; Chen, F. (2007) Ant - mediated seed dispersal contributes to the local spatial pattern and genetic structure of Globba lancangensis (Zingiberaceae). Journal of Heredity, 98 (4), 317 - 324. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1093 / jhered / esm 032" type="journal article" year="2007">
Zhou 
<emphasis box="[549,610,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
, 2007
</bibRefCitation>
), and one of us (CAS) frequently observed it in a rainforest in peninsular 
<collectingCountry box="[276,382,692,717]" name="Malaysia" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Levy, R." box="[395,536,692,717]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="331 - 340" refId="ref151183" refString="Levy, R. (1996) Interspecific colony dispersion and niche relations of three large tropical rain forest ant species. Tropical Rainforest, 74, 331 - 340. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 94 - 009 - 1685 - 2 _ 33" type="journal article" year="1996">Levy (1996)</bibRefCitation>
reported a density of 3,000 nest entrances per hectare in a Bornean rainforest. Colonies have over 
<specimenCount box="[384,529,727,752]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" type="worker">100 workers</specimenCount>
, and the polydomous subterranean nests are linked by interconnecting tunnels (
<bibRefCitation author="Berghoff, S. M. &amp; Maschwitz, U. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E." box="[158,398,764,789]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="149 - 157" refId="ref132637" refString="Berghoff, S. M., Maschwitz, U. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E. (2003) Influence of the hypogaeic army ant Dorylus (Dichthadia) laevigatus on tropical arthropod communities. Oecologia, 135, 149 - 157." type="journal article" year="2003">
Berghoff 
<emphasis box="[267,323,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
, 2003
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
<taxonomicName box="[199,363,799,824]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,363,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
workers are predominantly epigeic foragers and are generalist predators and scavengers (
<bibRefCitation author="Levy, R." pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="331 - 340" refId="ref151183" refString="Levy, R. (1996) Interspecific colony dispersion and niche relations of three large tropical rain forest ant species. Tropical Rainforest, 74, 331 - 340. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 94 - 009 - 1685 - 2 _ 33" type="journal article" year="1996">Levy, 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hashimoto, Y. &amp; Yamane, S. &amp; Itioka, T." box="[222,477,836,861]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="688 - 695" refId="ref145615" refString="Hashimoto, Y., Yamane, S. &amp; Itioka, T. (1997) A preliminary study on dietary habits of ants in a Bornean rain forest. Japanese Journal of Entomology, 65 (4), 688 - 695." type="journal article" year="1997">Hashimoto et al, 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Berghoff, S. M. &amp; Maschwitz, U. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E." box="[488,727,836,861]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="149 - 157" refId="ref132637" refString="Berghoff, S. M., Maschwitz, U. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E. (2003) Influence of the hypogaeic army ant Dorylus (Dichthadia) laevigatus on tropical arthropod communities. Oecologia, 135, 149 - 157." type="journal article" year="2003">
Berghoff 
<emphasis box="[596,654,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
, 2003
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pfeiffer, M. &amp; Nais, J. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E." box="[740,965,836,861]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="685 - 693" refId="ref160119" refString="Pfeiffer, M., Nais, J. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E. (2006) Worker size and seed size selection in ' seed' - collecting ant ensembles (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) in primary rain forests on Borneo. Journal of Tropical Ecology, 22, 685 - 693. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0266467406003622" type="journal article" year="2006">
Pfeiffer 
<emphasis box="[833,890,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
, 2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhou, H. &amp; Chen, J. &amp; Chen, F." box="[977,1177,836,861]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="317 - 324" refId="ref169966" refString="Zhou, H., Chen, J. &amp; Chen, F. (2007) Ant - mediated seed dispersal contributes to the local spatial pattern and genetic structure of Globba lancangensis (Zingiberaceae). Journal of Heredity, 98 (4), 317 - 324. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1093 / jhered / esm 032" type="journal article" year="2007">
Zhou 
<emphasis box="[1044,1101,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
, 2007
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Wheeler, W. M. &amp; Chapman, J. W." pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="47 - 73" refId="ref168181" refString="Wheeler, W. M. &amp; Chapman, J. W. (1925) The ants of the Philippine Islands. Part I, Dorylinae and Ponerinae. Philippine Journal of Science, 28, 47 - 73." type="journal article" year="1925">Wheeler &amp; Chapman (1925)</bibRefCitation>
noted that, in the 
<collectingCountry box="[434,563,871,896]" name="Philippines" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Philippines</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[576,740,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[576,740,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
“is especially fond of termites and is often seen raiding their colonies.” Remarkably, 
<bibRefCitation author="Berghoff, S. M. &amp; Maschwitz, U. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E." box="[421,668,908,933]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="149 - 157" refId="ref132637" refString="Berghoff, S. M., Maschwitz, U. &amp; Linsenmair, K. E. (2003) Influence of the hypogaeic army ant Dorylus (Dichthadia) laevigatus on tropical arthropod communities. Oecologia, 135, 149 - 157." type="journal article" year="2003">
Berghoff 
<emphasis box="[529,586,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
(2003)
</bibRefCitation>
observed that 
<taxonomicName box="[834,998,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[834,998,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
workers are effective at guarding their nest entrances from marauding 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[528,618,943,968]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dorylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[528,618,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Dorylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
army ants and that the 
<taxonomicName box="[916,1080,943,968]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[916,1080,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
workers actually prey on the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[151,241,980,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dorylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,241,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Dorylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Ants and termites made up nearly half of the food items collected by 
<taxonomicName box="[1044,1197,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transversa">
<emphasis box="[1044,1197,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">O. transversa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
workers in the study by 
<bibRefCitation author="Levy, R." box="[186,328,1015,1040]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="331 - 340" refId="ref151183" refString="Levy, R. (1996) Interspecific colony dispersion and niche relations of three large tropical rain forest ant species. Tropical Rainforest, 74, 331 - 340. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 94 - 009 - 1685 - 2 _ 33" type="journal article" year="1996">Levy (1996)</bibRefCitation>
. Workers only forage within about a meter from the nest entrances (
<bibRefCitation author="Eguchi, K. &amp; Bui, T. V. &amp; Yamane, S." box="[1088,1307,1015,1040]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="445 - 457" refId="ref140371" refString="Eguchi, K., Bui, T. V. &amp; Yamane, S. (2004) A preliminary study on foraging distance and nesting sites of ants in indo-Chinese lowland vegetation (Insects, Hymenoptera, Formicidae). Sociobiology, 43 (3), 445 - 457." type="journal article" year="2004">
Eguchi 
<emphasis box="[1176,1233,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
<bibRefCitation author="Morgan, E. D. &amp; do Nascimento, R. R. &amp; Keegans, S. J. &amp; Billen, J." box="[199,432,1052,1077]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="1395 - 1409" refId="ref156388" refString="Morgan, E. D., do Nascimento, R. R., Keegans, S. J. &amp; Billen, J. (1999) Comparative study of mandibular gland secretions of workers of ponerine ants. Journal of Chemical Ecology, 25 (6), 1395 - 1409. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1023 / a: 1020987028163" type="journal article" year="1999">
Morgan 
<emphasis box="[296,355,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
(1999
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Morgan, E. D. &amp; Jungnickel, H. &amp; Keegans, S. J. &amp; do Nascimento, R. R. &amp; Billen, J. &amp; Gobin, B. &amp; Ito, F." box="[446,504,1052,1077]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="95 - 114" refId="ref156304" refString="Morgan, E. D., Jungnickel, H., Keegans, S. J., do Nascimento, R. R., Billen, J., Gobin, B. &amp; Ito, F. (2003) Comparative survey of abdominal gland secretions of the ant subfamily Ponerinae. Journal of Chemical Ecology, 29 (1), 95 - 114. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1023 / a: 1021928630441" type="journal article" year="2003">2003</bibRefCitation>
) studied the mandibular gland and abdominal gland secretions of 
<taxonomicName box="[1266,1429,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1266,1429,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Leluk, J. &amp; Schmidt, J. &amp; Jones, D." box="[198,408,1087,1112]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="105 - 114" refId="ref150647" refString="Leluk, J., Schmidt, J. &amp; Jones, D. (1989) Comparative studies on the protein composition of the hymenoptera venom reservoirs. Toxicon, 27 (1), 105 - 114. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / 0041 - 0101 (89) 90410 - 8" type="journal article" year="1989">
Leluk 
<emphasis box="[270,327,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">et al.</emphasis>
(1989)
</bibRefCitation>
examined the protein composition of 
<taxonomicName box="[834,997,1087,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[834,997,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
venom.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,723,1124,1149]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Phylogenetic and taxonomic considerations.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[730,894,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[730,894,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was erected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mayr, G." box="[1075,1218,1124,1149]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="649 - 776" refId="ref155085" refString="Mayr, G. (1862) Myrmecologische Studien. Verhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Zoologisch-Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 12, 649 - 776." type="journal article" year="1862">Mayr (1862)</bibRefCitation>
to house the single species 
<taxonomicName authority="F. Smith" authorityName="F. Smith" box="[245,582,1159,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticulata">
<emphasis box="[245,467,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Ponera denticulata</emphasis>
F. Smith
</taxonomicName>
(now a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName box="[925,1084,1160,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transversa">
<emphasis box="[925,1084,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">O. transversa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The genus has experienced complete taxonomic stability at the genus level, as all subsequent authors have continued to treat it as a distinct genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="120.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">
We also consider 
<taxonomicName box="[404,567,1268,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[404,567,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be distinct from other genera. 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt, C." box="[960,1153,1268,1293]" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" pagination="201 - 250" refId="ref161753" refString="Schmidt, C. (2013) Molecular phylogenetics of ponerine ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae: Ponerinae). Zootaxa, 3647 (2), 201 - 250. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3647.2.1" type="journal article" year="2013">Schmidt's (2013)</bibRefCitation>
molecular phylogeny of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,263,1303,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ponerinae">Ponerinae</taxonomicName>
places 
<taxonomicName box="[359,523,1303,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[359,523,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with strong support within the 
<taxonomicName box="[910,1080,1303,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontomachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[910,1080,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontomachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, but its sister group is unresolved. Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName box="[499,663,1340,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[499,663,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has several autapomorphies (denticulate clypeal margin, pronotal spines, and denticulate-emarginate petiolar scale) which readily distinguish it from other ponerines. Its deep striate sculpturing is also unique within the 
<taxonomicName box="[588,758,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontomachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[588,758,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontomachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<taxonomicName box="[854,996,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Paltothyreus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[854,996,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Paltothyreus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has only shallow striate sculpturing), though 
<taxonomicName box="[244,367,1448,1471]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Diacamma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[244,367,1448,1471]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Diacamma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[440,614,1449,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ectomomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[440,614,1449,1472]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Ectomomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Emery" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[718,800,1449,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[718,800,1449,1472]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Ponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group have both convergently evolved deep striate sculpturing. In short, there are no morphological characters suggesting a close relationship with any other particular genus. 
<taxonomicName box="[362,526,1519,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[362,526,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is apparently yet another product of the early explosive radiation of the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,321,1556,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontomachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="120" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,321,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="120" pageNumber="121">Odontomachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
